olaos</i>, derived from <i>nikē</i> ‘victory’ + <i>laos</i> ‘people’. The spelling with <i>-ch-</i> first occurred as early as the 12th century, and became firmly established at the time of the Reformation, although  <b>Nicolas</b>  is still occasionally found.  St Nicholas  was a 4th-century bishop of Myra in Lycia, about whom virtually nothing factual is known, although a vast body of legend grew up around him, and he became the patron saint of Greece and of Russia, as well as of children, sailors, merchants, and pawnbrokers. His feast day is  6 December , and among the many roles which legend has assigned to him is that of bringer of Christmas presents, in the guise of ‘Santa Claus’ (an alteration of the Dutch form of his name, <i>Sinterklaas</i>)."]}]},{"name":"Jakobsen","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Scandinavian Bjorn, Lars, Anders, Bent, Gunner, Knut, Nels, Niels, Sven, Thor, Tor.","Danish, Norwegian, North German, and Dutch: patronymic from the personal name   Jakob  . Compare   Jacobsen   and   Jacobson  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Jakob","meanings":["spelling of   Jacob  , now also used in the English-speaking world."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Niels Jakobsen Bugge was born about 1235, in Hegnet, Tøndering, Harre, Viborg, Denmark, his father, Turild Bugge, was 22 and his mother, Turild Jacobsdatter, was 27. He had at least 1 son with Andersdatter. He died about 1310, in Lyby, Lyby, Nørre, Viborg, Denmark, at the age of 77."},"et":{"About 1235–About 1310":"umbes 1235–umbes 1310","1235–1310":"1235–1310","1240–Male":"1240–Surnud","1245–Female":"1245–Surnud","1225–Female":"1225–Surnud","1270–1332":"1270–1332","1215–1302":"1215–1302","1210–1270":"1210–1270","about 1270":"umbes 1270","About 1235":"umbes 1235","Abt 1302":"umbes 1302","1240":"1240","About 1310":"umbes 1310","1270":"1270","About 1270":"umbes 1270","1215":"1215","1302":"1302","1225":"1225","1235":"